data.content:
Here's the improved version using proper MSTest assertions:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive)); // no built-in predicate assert
    var admin = users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin");
    Assert.IsNotNull(admin);
}
```

**Key replacements:**

| Instead of | Use |
|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count > 0)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count)` — since you already know the expected count |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count)` — gives a clear failure message with expected vs actual |
| `Assert.IsTrue(obj != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(obj)` — dedicated null check with better diagnostics |

**Other useful `CollectionAssert` methods:**

- `CollectionAssert.Contains(collection, element)` — item exists
- `CollectionAssert.DoesNotContain(collection, element)` — item absent
- `CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreUnique(collection)` — no duplicates
- `CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual)` — same order & elements
- `CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual)` — same elements, any order

> **Note:** MSTest doesn't have a built-in "all items match predicate" assertion, so `Assert.IsTrue(users.All(...))` is acceptable there. If you want richer collection assertions with lambdas, consider adding [FluentAssertions](https://fluentassertions.com/) (`users.Should().OnlyContain(u => u.IsActive)`).
